<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="107" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,438,1795]" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,438,463]" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. The male of this species is similar to those of 
<taxonomicName box="[820,1066,438,462]" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Microptila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orienthula">
<emphasis box="[820,1066,438,462]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">Microptila orienthula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the Vietnamese 
<taxonomicName authority="Olah and Johanson 2010" authorityName="Olah and Johanson" authorityYear="2010" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Microptila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dironga">
<emphasis box="[1308,1436,438,462]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">M. dironga</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Olah" box="[151,432,474,499]" pageId="3" pageNumber="107" refString="Olah, J. &amp; Johanson, K. A. (2010) Description of 46 new Old World Hydroptilidae. Folia Entomologica Hungarica, 71, 65 - 155." type="journal article" year="2010">Oláh and Johanson 2010</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but can be distinguished from these as follows: (1) Segment IX has a broader tegmental bridge (
<emphasis box="[240,260,511,535]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">cf</emphasis>
. the very narrow bridge in 
<taxonomicName box="[574,729,510,534]" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Microptila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orienthula">
<emphasis box="[574,729,510,534]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">M. orienthula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[786,913,510,534]" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Microptila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dironga">
<emphasis box="[786,913,510,534]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">M. dironga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), with the dorsal midline about 1/5 as long as segment IX (
<figureCitation box="[299,368,546,571]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1861,1883]" captionTargetBox="[276,1315,418,1833]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[262,1325,409,1837]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Microptila genka sp. nov. male and female, type specimens. Male (2 A – 2 F): 2 A, genitalia, left lateral; 2 B, same, dorsal; 2 C, same, ventral; 2 D, subgenital plate, dorsal; 2 E, right inferior appendage, ventromesal; 2 F, phallus, left lateral. Female (2 G): 2 G, abdominal segments VII – X, ventral. Abbreviations: VII – X = abdominal segments VII – X; inf app = inferior appendage (paired); ph = phallus; sg plate = subgenital plate; ti = titillator; t X = tergite X." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/292745/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
B); (2) the subgenital plate is rounded caudally (
<figureCitation box="[919,998,546,571]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1861,1883]" captionTargetBox="[276,1315,418,1833]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[262,1325,409,1837]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Microptila genka sp. nov. male and female, type specimens. Male (2 A – 2 F): 2 A, genitalia, left lateral; 2 B, same, dorsal; 2 C, same, ventral; 2 D, subgenital plate, dorsal; 2 E, right inferior appendage, ventromesal; 2 F, phallus, left lateral. Female (2 G): 2 G, abdominal segments VII – X, ventral. Abbreviations: VII – X = abdominal segments VII – X; inf app = inferior appendage (paired); ph = phallus; sg plate = subgenital plate; ti = titillator; t X = tergite X." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/292745/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">Figs. 2</figureCitation>
B, 2D, 
<emphasis box="[1080,1100,547,571]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">cf</emphasis>
. the plate has a tiny U- or Vshaped excavation caudally in 
<taxonomicName box="[504,661,582,606]" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Microptila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orienthula">
<emphasis box="[504,661,582,606]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">M. orienthula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); and (3) the inferior appendages are stout with thick setose ridges mesally (
<figureCitation box="[254,332,618,643]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1861,1883]" captionTargetBox="[276,1315,418,1833]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[262,1325,409,1837]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Microptila genka sp. nov. male and female, type specimens. Male (2 A – 2 F): 2 A, genitalia, left lateral; 2 B, same, dorsal; 2 C, same, ventral; 2 D, subgenital plate, dorsal; 2 E, right inferior appendage, ventromesal; 2 F, phallus, left lateral. Female (2 G): 2 G, abdominal segments VII – X, ventral. Abbreviations: VII – X = abdominal segments VII – X; inf app = inferior appendage (paired); ph = phallus; sg plate = subgenital plate; ti = titillator; t X = tergite X." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/292745/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">Figs. 2</figureCitation>
A, 2C, 2E, 
<emphasis box="[460,480,619,643]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">cf</emphasis>
. the rather slender appendages in 
<taxonomicName box="[867,993,619,643]" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Microptila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dironga">
<emphasis box="[867,993,619,643]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">M. dironga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Females of this species are similar to those of 
<taxonomicName box="[249,404,654,678]" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Microptila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orienthula">
<emphasis box="[249,404,654,678]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">M. orienthula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but can be distinguished from the latter by the presence of a triangular median process on the caudal margin of segment VII (
<figureCitation box="[581,653,690,715]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1861,1883]" captionTargetBox="[276,1315,418,1833]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[262,1325,409,1837]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Microptila genka sp. nov. male and female, type specimens. Male (2 A – 2 F): 2 A, genitalia, left lateral; 2 B, same, dorsal; 2 C, same, ventral; 2 D, subgenital plate, dorsal; 2 E, right inferior appendage, ventromesal; 2 F, phallus, left lateral. Female (2 G): 2 G, abdominal segments VII – X, ventral. Abbreviations: VII – X = abdominal segments VII – X; inf app = inferior appendage (paired); ph = phallus; sg plate = subgenital plate; ti = titillator; t X = tergite X." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/292745/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
G, 
<emphasis box="[691,711,691,715]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">cf</emphasis>
. the caudal margin of segment VII is wholly convex in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Microptila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="orienthula">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">M. orienthula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="107" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,438,1795]" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,260,762,787]" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">Male</emphasis>
. Length of each forewing and hind wing 
<quantity box="[740,877,762,787]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.65" metricValueMax="1.7" metricValueMin="1.6" pageId="3" pageNumber="107" unit="mm" value="1.65" valueMax="1.7" valueMin="1.6">1.6–1.7 mm</quantity>
and 
<quantity box="[935,1074,762,787]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.45" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="1.4" pageId="3" pageNumber="107" unit="mm" value="1.45" valueMax="1.5" valueMin="1.4">1.4–1.5 mm</quantity>
, respectively (n = 3). Antennae each 19-segmented and 
<quantity box="[421,556,798,823]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="107" unit="mm" value="0.55" valueMax="0.6" valueMin="0.5">0.5–0.6 mm</quantity>
long (n = 3).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,438,1795]" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">
Genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[320,401,834,859]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1861,1883]" captionTargetBox="[276,1315,418,1833]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[262,1325,409,1837]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Microptila genka sp. nov. male and female, type specimens. Male (2 A – 2 F): 2 A, genitalia, left lateral; 2 B, same, dorsal; 2 C, same, ventral; 2 D, subgenital plate, dorsal; 2 E, right inferior appendage, ventromesal; 2 F, phallus, left lateral. Female (2 G): 2 G, abdominal segments VII – X, ventral. Abbreviations: VII – X = abdominal segments VII – X; inf app = inferior appendage (paired); ph = phallus; sg plate = subgenital plate; ti = titillator; t X = tergite X." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/292745/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">Figs. 2</figureCitation>
A–2F). Segment IX (IX) annular, in dorsal view (
<figureCitation box="[985,1056,834,859]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1861,1883]" captionTargetBox="[276,1315,418,1833]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[262,1325,409,1837]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Microptila genka sp. nov. male and female, type specimens. Male (2 A – 2 F): 2 A, genitalia, left lateral; 2 B, same, dorsal; 2 C, same, ventral; 2 D, subgenital plate, dorsal; 2 E, right inferior appendage, ventromesal; 2 F, phallus, left lateral. Female (2 G): 2 G, abdominal segments VII – X, ventral. Abbreviations: VII – X = abdominal segments VII – X; inf app = inferior appendage (paired); ph = phallus; sg plate = subgenital plate; ti = titillator; t X = tergite X." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/292745/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
B) excavation of anterior margin semi-circular, excavation of posterior margin broadly concave; transverse tegmental bridge broad, dorsal midline about 1/5 as long as segment IX; in ventral view (
<figureCitation box="[756,827,906,931]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1861,1883]" captionTargetBox="[276,1315,418,1833]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[262,1325,409,1837]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Microptila genka sp. nov. male and female, type specimens. Male (2 A – 2 F): 2 A, genitalia, left lateral; 2 B, same, dorsal; 2 C, same, ventral; 2 D, subgenital plate, dorsal; 2 E, right inferior appendage, ventromesal; 2 F, phallus, left lateral. Female (2 G): 2 G, abdominal segments VII – X, ventral. Abbreviations: VII – X = abdominal segments VII – X; inf app = inferior appendage (paired); ph = phallus; sg plate = subgenital plate; ti = titillator; t X = tergite X." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/292745/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
C) excavation of anterior margin broadly triangular, excavation of posterior margin wide and shallow. Tergite X (t X) semimembranous, transparent, with lightly sclerotized lateral and caudal margins, quadrate, with deep and wide triangular excavation caudally in dorsal view (
<figureCitation box="[159,227,1014,1039]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1861,1883]" captionTargetBox="[276,1315,418,1833]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[262,1325,409,1837]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Microptila genka sp. nov. male and female, type specimens. Male (2 A – 2 F): 2 A, genitalia, left lateral; 2 B, same, dorsal; 2 C, same, ventral; 2 D, subgenital plate, dorsal; 2 E, right inferior appendage, ventromesal; 2 F, phallus, left lateral. Female (2 G): 2 G, abdominal segments VII – X, ventral. Abbreviations: VII – X = abdominal segments VII – X; inf app = inferior appendage (paired); ph = phallus; sg plate = subgenital plate; ti = titillator; t X = tergite X." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/292745/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
B). Subgenital plate (sg plate) twice as long as tergite X, elongate ovate, rounded caudally, semimembranous with lightly sclerotized lateral margins (
<figureCitation box="[599,677,1050,1075]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1861,1883]" captionTargetBox="[276,1315,418,1833]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[262,1325,409,1837]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Microptila genka sp. nov. male and female, type specimens. Male (2 A – 2 F): 2 A, genitalia, left lateral; 2 B, same, dorsal; 2 C, same, ventral; 2 D, subgenital plate, dorsal; 2 E, right inferior appendage, ventromesal; 2 F, phallus, left lateral. Female (2 G): 2 G, abdominal segments VII – X, ventral. Abbreviations: VII – X = abdominal segments VII – X; inf app = inferior appendage (paired); ph = phallus; sg plate = subgenital plate; ti = titillator; t X = tergite X." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/292745/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">Figs. 2</figureCitation>
A, 2B, 2D). Inferior appendages (inf app) large, setose, without any branches; in ventral view (
<figureCitation box="[466,536,1086,1111]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1861,1883]" captionTargetBox="[276,1315,418,1833]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[262,1325,409,1837]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Microptila genka sp. nov. male and female, type specimens. Male (2 A – 2 F): 2 A, genitalia, left lateral; 2 B, same, dorsal; 2 C, same, ventral; 2 D, subgenital plate, dorsal; 2 E, right inferior appendage, ventromesal; 2 F, phallus, left lateral. Female (2 G): 2 G, abdominal segments VII – X, ventral. Abbreviations: VII – X = abdominal segments VII – X; inf app = inferior appendage (paired); ph = phallus; sg plate = subgenital plate; ti = titillator; t X = tergite X." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/292745/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
C) each with basal 2/3 stout, apical 1/3 slender, apex incurved and acute; in ventromesal view (
<figureCitation box="[376,448,1122,1147]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1861,1883]" captionTargetBox="[276,1315,418,1833]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[262,1325,409,1837]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Microptila genka sp. nov. male and female, type specimens. Male (2 A – 2 F): 2 A, genitalia, left lateral; 2 B, same, dorsal; 2 C, same, ventral; 2 D, subgenital plate, dorsal; 2 E, right inferior appendage, ventromesal; 2 F, phallus, left lateral. Female (2 G): 2 G, abdominal segments VII – X, ventral. Abbreviations: VII – X = abdominal segments VII – X; inf app = inferior appendage (paired); ph = phallus; sg plate = subgenital plate; ti = titillator; t X = tergite X." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/292745/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
E) basal 2/3 with longitudinal setose ridge mesally and apical 1/3 rectangular with strongly sclerotized ridge. Phallus long with slender, elongate titillator (ti) arising near apical 1/4, titillator encircling phallus 1.5 times (
<figureCitation box="[476,543,1194,1219]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1861,1883]" captionTargetBox="[276,1315,418,1833]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[262,1325,409,1837]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Microptila genka sp. nov. male and female, type specimens. Male (2 A – 2 F): 2 A, genitalia, left lateral; 2 B, same, dorsal; 2 C, same, ventral; 2 D, subgenital plate, dorsal; 2 E, right inferior appendage, ventromesal; 2 F, phallus, left lateral. Female (2 G): 2 G, abdominal segments VII – X, ventral. Abbreviations: VII – X = abdominal segments VII – X; inf app = inferior appendage (paired); ph = phallus; sg plate = subgenital plate; ti = titillator; t X = tergite X." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/292745/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
F).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,438,1795]" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,286,1230,1255]" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">Female</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[303,373,1230,1255]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1861,1883]" captionTargetBox="[276,1315,418,1833]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[262,1325,409,1837]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Microptila genka sp. nov. male and female, type specimens. Male (2 A – 2 F): 2 A, genitalia, left lateral; 2 B, same, dorsal; 2 C, same, ventral; 2 D, subgenital plate, dorsal; 2 E, right inferior appendage, ventromesal; 2 F, phallus, left lateral. Female (2 G): 2 G, abdominal segments VII – X, ventral. Abbreviations: VII – X = abdominal segments VII – X; inf app = inferior appendage (paired); ph = phallus; sg plate = subgenital plate; ti = titillator; t X = tergite X." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/292745/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Length of each forewing and hind wing 
<quantity box="[859,996,1230,1255]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" metricValueMax="1.8" metricValueMin="1.6" pageId="3" pageNumber="107" unit="mm" value="1.7" valueMax="1.8" valueMin="1.6">1.6–1.8 mm</quantity>
and 
<quantity box="[1053,1192,1231,1255]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.35" metricValueMax="1.4" metricValueMin="1.3" pageId="3" pageNumber="107" unit="mm" value="1.35" valueMax="1.4" valueMin="1.3">1.3–1.4 mm</quantity>
, respectively (n = 4). Antennae each 19-segmented and 
<quantity box="[535,670,1266,1291]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="107" unit="mm" value="0.55" valueMax="0.6" valueMin="0.5">0.5–0.6 mm</quantity>
long (n = 4).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,438,1795]" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">
Abdominal segments I–VII densely covered with long thick setae. Segment VII (VII) tergite and sternite fused laterally, caudal margin with triangular median process in ventral view (
<figureCitation box="[967,1035,1338,1363]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1861,1883]" captionTargetBox="[276,1315,418,1833]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[262,1325,409,1837]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Microptila genka sp. nov. male and female, type specimens. Male (2 A – 2 F): 2 A, genitalia, left lateral; 2 B, same, dorsal; 2 C, same, ventral; 2 D, subgenital plate, dorsal; 2 E, right inferior appendage, ventromesal; 2 F, phallus, left lateral. Female (2 G): 2 G, abdominal segments VII – X, ventral. Abbreviations: VII – X = abdominal segments VII – X; inf app = inferior appendage (paired); ph = phallus; sg plate = subgenital plate; ti = titillator; t X = tergite X." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/292745/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="107">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
G). Segment VIII almost as long as segment VII, often withdrawn into segment VII.
</paragraph>
